Peroneus Longus Tears Associated With Pathology of the Os Peroneum > Kristopher G. Stockton, MD1, and James W. Brodsky, MD1
Abstract Background: There is a range of different types of tears and pathology of the peroneal tendons.
One of the least common types is the tear of the peroneus longus associated with fracture, enlargement, or entrapment at the cuboid tunnel of the os peroneum.
The purpose of this study was to evaluate the pathologic patterns of these uncommon peroneal tendon tears, to review the treatment, and to report the patient outcomes following treatment with excision of the os peroneum, debridement, and tenodesis of the peroneus longus to the peroneus brevis.

Peroneus Longus Tears Associated With Pathology of the Os Peroneum > Kristopher G. Stockton, MD1, and James W. Brodsky, MD1
Methods: A 5-year retrospective review of all patients with peroneal tendon tears identified 12 patients operatively treated for peroneus longus tendon tears with associated pathology of the os peroneum, and in whom there was a viable peroneus brevis.
All patients were treated with an operative procedure consisting of excision of the os peroneum, debridement, and tenodesis of the peroneus longus to the peroneus brevis.
Mean age was 51.5 (range, 33 to 73) years, including 7 males and 5 females.
Operative and radiographic records were reviewed to characterize the nature of the peroneus longus tears and associated pathology.
Preoperative and postoperative AOFAS hindfoot, SF-36 questionnaires, and Visual Analog Scale (VAS) pain scores were compiled and patient records were reviewed for complications.
Mean follow-up after surgery was 63.3 (range, 12 to 114) months.
Results: All of the patients had an os peroneum associated with a complex, irreparable tear of the peroneus longus tendon.
The peroneus longus was typically enlarged, fibrotic, and adhered to the surrounding tissues.
In 8 patients, the peroneus longus tendon tear was associated with a fracture of the os peroneum, and in 4 patients with an enlarged and entrapped os peroneum which prevented movement at the cuboid tunnel.
Of the 12 patients, 9 had partial tears of the peroneus brevis, which were treated with debridement and suture repair.
AOFAS hindfoot scores increased from a preoperative mean of 61 (range, 46 to 75) to a postoperative mean of 91.7 (range, 60 to 100).
Mean preoperative SF-36 Physical Component Scores (PCS) increased from 36 to 52 postoperatively.
Mean VAS pain scores decreased from a preoperative mean of 6.3 (range, 4 to 8) to a postoperative mean of 1.0 (range, 0 to 4).
Complications included 2 patients with sural neuritis and 3 with superficial delayed wound healing successfully treated nonoperatively.

Peroneus Longus Tears Associated With Pathology of the Os Peroneum > Kristopher G. Stockton, MD1, and James W. Brodsky, MD1
Conclusion: Tears of the distal peroneus longus tendon, which are much less commonly reported than tears of the peroneus brevis, can be associated with pathology of the os peroneum.
Excision of the os peroneum, tendon debridement, and tenodesis of the longus to brevis was an effective surgical technique.

Peroneus Longus Tears Associated With Pathology of the Os Peroneum > Kristopher G. Stockton, MD1, and James W. Brodsky, MD1
Level of Evidence: Level IV, case series.

Peroneus Longus Tears Associated With Pathology of the Os Peroneum > Kristopher G. Stockton, MD1, and James W. Brodsky, MD1
Keywords: os peroneum, peroneus longus, peroneal tendons In the differential diagnosis of lateral ankle and foot pain, disorders of the peroneal tendons are less commonly recog- nized than injuries of the lateral ligaments, perhaps because of the chronic nature of most peroneal tendon lesions.1,10,19,20 However, awareness of tears of the peroneal tendons is increasing, as evidenced by multiple published series of these patients.
Multiple authors have reported on a range of peroneal tendon problems other than tendon tears, includ- ing symptoms caused by low-lying peroneal muscle belly6,7,23,24 and peroneal tendon subluxation.6,10,14,19,23,24 Authors have also reported on different patterns and combi- nations of tears of the peroneal tendons, including isolated tears of the peroneus brevis10 and tears of both tendons.9,20 Isolated tears of the peroneus longus are the least frequently reported among these.

Peroneus Longus Tears Associated With Pathology of the Os Peroneum > Kristopher G. Stockton, MD1, and James W. Brodsky, MD1
There are a number of case reports, but only a few series published on the results of operative treatment of peroneus longus tendon tears, with only 3 series reporting on more than 10 patients.3,21,23 Even less frequently cited are cases in which 1Baylor University Medical Center, Dallas, TX, USA

the tears of the peroneus longus are associated with pathology of the os peroneum.
Sobel et al reported on 10 patients with pain and pathology of the os peroneum, of whom 8 were treated operatively.25 Sammarco et al noted the presence of an os peroneum in 6 of 14 cases of patients with tears of the peroneus longus tendon.21 Peterson and Stinson reported the results of os excision and primary repair of the peroneus longus in 5 patients with fractures of the os peroneum.17 The purpose of this study was to report the operative findings, clinical results, and outcome scores of operatively treated patients with peroneus longus tears associated with os peroneum pathology.

Peroneus Longus Tears Associated With Pathology of the Os Peroneum > Methods
Over a 5-year period, 12 patients were treated operatively for peroneus longus tendon tears associated with pathology of the os peroneum, in whom there was also a viable or reparable peroneus brevis.
Patients with irreparable tears of both peroneal tendons were excluded from this study.
Review was done of the patients’ medical records for demographic data, operative findings, operative procedures, complications, and subsequent operations.
Preoperative and postoperative outcome measures included the AOFAS Ankle-Hindfoot score, the Visual Analog Scale (VAS) for pain, and the SF-36 questionnaire.
Radiographs and imaging studies were reviewed for findings of fracture of the os peroneum and tears of the peroneal tendons.

Peroneus Longus Tears Associated With Pathology of the Os Peroneum > Methods
Mean age at the time of operative intervention in 7 male and 5 female patients was 51.5 (range, 33 to 73) years (Table 1).
All patients had failed conservative management consisting of NSAIDs, immobilization, bracing, and physical therapy.
Mean follow-up from operation was 63.3 (range, 12 to 114) months.

Peroneus Longus Tears Associated With Pathology of the Os Peroneum > Methods
Operative protocol consisted of excision of the damaged segment of the peroneus longus, including the os peroneum, followed by tenodesis to the peroneus brevis with the ankle and hindfoot in neutral alignment.
Concomitant tears of the peroneus brevis were debrided and repaired prior to tenodesis.
Hypertrophic peroneal tubercles of the calcaneus were excised where the surgical findings revealed this as an obvious mechanical cause of splitting of the peroneus longus tendon.
Reconstruction of the superior peroneal retinaculum was done in all cases.
All procedures were done by a single fellowship-trained orthopaedic foot and ankle surgeon (JWB).
Postoperatively, patients were kept nonweight-bearing in a short leg cast for 4 weeks and weight-bearing in a cast for 4 weeks, and then transitioned to a removable boot for 4 weeks.
Initiation of physical therapy began at 12 weeks.

Peroneus Longus Tears Associated With Pathology of the Os Peroneum > Results > Operative Findings
All patients had a primary peroneus longus tendon tear with an associated abnormality of the os peroneum.
Presenting symptoms included lateral ankle and/or foot pain, swelling, tenderness, weakness, and functional instability.
Six patients had a cavovarus foot.
Concomitant pathology included a talar osteochondral lesion, and calcaneocuboid arthritis, in 1 patient each.
These patients underwent arthroscopic debridement of the ankle and calcaneocuboid arthrodesis, respectively, during the same operation for reconstruction of the peroneus longus.

Peroneus Longus Tears Associated With Pathology of the Os Peroneum > Results > Operative Findings
Intraoperatively, all of the patients in this series had an os peroneum present and tears of the peroneus longus tendon that were irreparable (Figures 1 and 2).
In 8 cases, the peroneus longus tendon degeneration and splitting was associated with a fracture of the os peroneum and occurred in the distal portion of the peroneus longus tendon (Figures 3 and 4).

The remaining 4 had an enlarged, degenerative os peroneum that was adhered to the surrounding tissue and prevented movement of the longus at the cuboid tunnel.
Nine of the 12 patients were found to have peroneus brevis tears of a lesser severity than the damage to the peroneus longus.
In each of these cases, the peroneus brevis was salvageable and treated with debridement and suture repair.
Four patients also were found to have a hypertrophied peroneal tubercle of the calcaneus (Figure 5) that was splitting or fraying the peroneus longus in that zone (Table 2).
Ten patients had subluxating or dislocating peroneal tendons and superior retinacular reconstruction was done in these cases.

Peroneus Longus Tears Associated With Pathology of the Os Peroneum > Results > Operative Procedures
All 12 patients had excision of the damaged segment of the peroneus longus, including the fractured or enlarged os peroneum.
In each case, the peroneus longus was tenodesed to the peroneus brevis while holding the ankle and hindfoot in neutral position.
The superior tenodesis was done above the tear in the peroneus longus, between the tip of the fibula and the peroneal tubercle of the calcaneus.
The distal stump was tenodesed at or just proximal to the cuboid tunnel.
Concomitant debridement and repair of the brevis was required in 9 of 12 cases, and excision of a hypertrophied peroneal tubercle in 4 of 12 (Table 2).

Peroneus Longus Tears Associated With Pathology of the Os Peroneum > Results > Complications and Subsequent Operations
Complications included 2 patients with sural neuritis, 3 with superficial delayed wound healing successfully treated nonoperatively, and 1 with symptomatic hardware from a concomitant calcaneocuboid arthrodesis requiring subsequent hardware removal (Table 2).
One patient required bracing for activities of daily living.
One patient did well for 6 years postoperatively, but had subsequent treatment for an osteochondroma of the distal fibula, with pain and a new tear of the peroneus brevis, to which the longus was previously tenodesed.
She underwent reconstruction at another facility with repair of the brevis tear with supplementation with dermal allograft 6 months prior to this report.

Peroneus Longus Tears Associated With Pathology of the Os Peroneum > Results > Results of Outcome Scores
All 12 patients completed the postoperative AOFAS hindfoot, SF-36, and VAS scores, but complete preoperative scores were identified in only 7 of the 12 patients.
None of the available outcomes data were excluded.
Mean preoperative AOFAS hindfoot scores increased from 61 (range, 46 to 75) to 91.7 (range, 60 to 100) postoperatively.
Mean preoperative SF-36 physical component scores increased from 36 (range, 24 to 50) to 52 (range, 44 to 60) postoperatively.
Mean VAS pain scores decreased from 6.3 (range, 4 to 8) to 1.0 (range, 0 to 4) postoperatively.
All had a decrease in VAS scores postoperatively.
All but 1 patient had an increase in AOFAS and SF-36 physical component scores.

Peroneus Longus Tears Associated With Pathology of the Os Peroneum > Results > Radiographic and MRI Findings
Fractures of the os peroneum were diagnosed on the preop- erative radiographs performed in the clinic, in 7 of the 8 patients with fracture (Figure 6).
Of the 8 patients with os peroneum fractures, 7 of them also had preoperative MRI to evaluate the extent and nature of tendon involvement.
In only 1 of these 7 MRIs did the radiologic interpretation accurately identify the fracture of os peroneum in addition to the tendon changes (Figure 7).
The 1 patient who did not have an MRI had wide displacement of the fracture frag- ments of the os peroneum on radiographs.
One MRI identi- fied edema within the os peroneum but no definitive fracture and another patient obtained a preoperative CT scan that showed a nondisplaced fracture of the os peroneum, which was not seen on MRI or radiograph.
Radiographic findings in the absence of fracture included degeneration and enlarge- ment of the os peroneum noted on preoperative radiographs in 4 cases, which at the time of surgery was noted to be asso- ciated with degenerative tearing of the distal peroneus lon- gus just at or proximal to the cuboid tunnel.

Ten of the 12 patients had a preoperative MRI, of which many came from outside institutions, and which was the source of the variable accuracy of the radiologic interpretations regarding the details of the peroneal tendon tears.
In each patient, the MRI correctly identified the presence of a torn peroneal tendon, but in 3 of the ten, pathology of the brevis tendon was identified, while the tear of the longus tendon was not.
The other 7 of 10 correctly identified the longus tear but the severity was underestimated compared to the intraoperative findings.
These patients were treated in a tertiary referral center, and the MRI scans were not repeated due to considerations of cost to the patient.
While we believe that the accuracy of peroneal MRI studies in our institution is excellent, attributable to the expertise of our musculoskeletal radiology specialists, the variable accuracy of many of the outside MRI studies reflects the need for expertise in musculoskeletal radiology for these cases.

Peroneus Longus Tears Associated With Pathology of the Os Peroneum > Discussion
The os peroneum is an accessory ossicle within the substance of the distal peroneus longus tendon.
Various authors have estimated its incidence in the population anywhere between 4% and 30% of the population.3,8,22,25,27 It normally lies adjacent to the cuboid notch or the calcaneocuboid joint as seen on plain radiographs.
Proximal migration of the os peroneum is a useful marker of tendon disruption in acute and chronic injuries,22,26,27 but it must be distinguished from other accessory ossicles of the hindfoot.

Peroneus Longus Tears Associated With Pathology of the Os Peroneum > Discussion
Pathology of the peroneus longus should be included in the differential diagnosis of lateral hindfoot and midfoot pain, with particular attention to anatomic zones that are easy to identify on physical examination, for instance the peroneal tubercle of the lateral calcaneus and the cuboid tunnel, just proximal to the base of the fifth metatarsal.

Peroneus Longus Tears Associated With Pathology of the Os Peroneum > Discussion
These are the areas of physical stress on the tendon, as postulated by previous authors3 and as documented on operative findings in this series.

Peroneus Longus Tears Associated With Pathology of the Os Peroneum > Discussion
Brandes and Smith described 3 anatomic areas in which the peroneus longus tendon changes direction, and their association with tendon tears.
Zone A, at the tip of the fibula, was least associated with longus tears; zone B, at the peroneal tubercle of the calcaneus, had the highest incidence of partial ruptures; and zone C, at the cuboid notch, had the highest incidence of complete ruptures.3 All of the cases in this series had pathology in zones B and C, similar to their classification.

Peroneus Longus Tears Associated With Pathology of the Os Peroneum > Discussion
Unlike the study by Jockel and Brodsky,9 which reported on severe, unsalvageable, concomitant tears of the peroneus longus and peroneus brevis tendons, our cases did not require reconstruction using transfer of the flexor digitorum longus or flexor hallucis longus tendon, because in each of these cases the peroneus brevis tendon was viable.
However, it is worth recognizing that these cases occur over a spectrum of peroneal tendon pathology, rather than within rigid categories.
The key difference in this series was the advantage afforded by the retention of a functional peroneus brevis tendon.

Peroneus Longus Tears Associated With Pathology of the Os Peroneum > Discussion
There is a relative paucity of literature which examines this particular pathology.
Most publications consist of single case reports2,5,11,12,15,16,18,26,28 or reports of series of 2 to 5 patients.4,13,17,22,27 Thompson and Patterson reported on 3 patients with peroneus longus ruptures distal to the os peroneum.
All of the patients had abnormal position of the os as seen on radiographs and were treated with excision of abnormal tendon and os with tenodesis to the brevis proximally.
All 3 of the patients were described as pain free except for a second metatarsal stress fracture which developed in 1 patient 4 years postoperatively.27 Peterson and Stinson reported on 5 patients with fractures of the os peroneum, treated with excision of the os and peroneus longus repair.17 Bruce et al reported on 3 patients who had debridement of an enlarged peroneal tubercle and repair of the longus tendon at that level.4 Sammarco et al reported on 2 patients that underwent partial excision of the fractured os peroneum with primary repair.22 Maurer and Lehrman reported on 2 patients with fractures of the os peroneum treated with excision of the proximal fracture piece and associated tendon and tenodesis to peroneus brevis proximal to the lateral malleolus.13 To the best of our knowledge, there are only 3 larger series focusing primarily on peroneus longus tears to date.
Not all report the details of operative technique and the reported techniques are heterogeneous.
None report objective outcomes data.
Sobel et al reported on 8 operatively treated patients with os peroneum fractures, of whom, 2 underwent excision of the os and primary tendon repair, and 6 underwent os excision with tenodesis of the peroneus longus to peroneus brevis.25 Sammarco et al reported on 14 operatively treated patients with primarily peroneus longus pathology, of whom 8 had concomitant peroneus brevis tears and 6 had an os peroneum present.
The operative techniques in their series included primary repair of the peroneus longus tears in 10 patients; 3 patients underwent excision of the os peroneus, of whom 2 underwent primary tendon repair and 1 repair with a fascial graft; and 1 patient had the longus tendon tenodesed to the cuboid.21 Brandes and Smith reviewed 21 operatively treated cases with primarily peroneus longus pathology and reported on the pathological findings, but not on surgical technique or patient outcomes.
All 6 complete ruptures were in zone C and 8 of 9 partial tears were in zone B. There was a 33% incidence of concomitant peroneus brevis tears and 82% of patients had a cavovarus foot.3 Reported operative techniques include internal fixation of the fractured os peroneum,16 excision of all or part of the os peroneum with primary repair or grafting of the tendon gap,5,11,12,17,18,21,22,25,26 or excision of the os with tenodesis of peroneus longus to the peroneus brevis.13,23,25,27 The varied surgical techniques described in these articles make it difficult to make any conclusions regarding superiority of a given operative technique.
This series reports on the pathologic findings and the results of excision and tenodesis.
Excluding the single case reports, this was also reported by Thompson and Patterson in 3 patients,27 in 6 of the 8 operative cases reported by Sobel et al,25 in 5 of 41 patients by Saxena and Cassidy,23 and in 2 patients by Maurer and Lehrman.13 This series is 1 of the 3 largest of its kind reporting on primarily peroneus longus tendon tears and is the only one reporting outcomes data.
It is the largest series reporting results of a single operative technique that consisted of excision of the pathologic section of the peroneus longus tendon including the os peroneum with tenodesis of the peroneus longus to the peroneus brevis tendon.
This series also reports concomitant findings of the peroneus brevis tendon, which appear to be related to subluxation within the retinaculum, as noted by previous authors.10 This study has several limitations, including its retrospective nature and that some of the patients did not have preoperative outcome scores.
Despite that, this study reports the most complete outcomes data to date on this uncommon form of peroneal tendon tear, as well as information on the morphology and nature of peroneus longus tears associated with abnormalities of the os peroneum.

Some of the patients in this study underwent concomitant operative procedures and therefore, improvement in patient pain and function may not be entirely attributable to the peroneal reconstruction.
Nonetheless, peroneal related symptoms were the primary underlying diagnosis and the primary operative indication for all of these patients.

Peroneus Longus Tears Associated With Pathology of the Os Peroneum > Conclusion
Tenodesis of the peroneus longus to the peroneus brevis tendon with excision of the pathologic section of the longus tendon and the associated os peroneum improved patient pain and function when treating tears of the peroneus longus tendon associated with pathology of the os peroneum.
This study demonstrated objective improvements in prospectively collected AOFAS scores, SF-36 outcomes, and VAS pain measures.
